---
import Base from "../../layouts/Base.astro";
---

<Base
  title="Skeletor — Jeff Mills"
  description="A front-end component framework I built at Delphic Digital (2014–2017) with native Web Components in 2016. The architectural seed that became AXS nine years later."
>
  <p class="project-back"><a href="/projects">&laquo; all projects</a></p>
  <h1 class="page-title">skeletor</h1>
  <p class="project-meta">
    <span class="project-year">2014 — 2017</span>
    <span class="meta-sep">&middot;</span>
    <span class="project-status">archived</span>
    <span class="meta-sep">&middot;</span>
    <span>delphic digital</span>
    <span class="meta-sep">&middot;</span>
    <span>~12 repos</span>
  </p>

  <p class="page-lede">
    Skeletor was the front-end framework we built at Delphic Digital
    (Philadelphia, 2014&ndash;2017). It started as a Gulp + Sass boilerplate
    and grew into a multi-repo component system with native Web Components in
    2016 &mdash; years before the broader industry caught up. The same
    architectural instincts are what AXS scales today.
  </p>

  <aside class="callout">
    <span class="callout-label">The throughline</span>
    <p>
      Skeletor isn&rsquo;t in production anywhere now &mdash; the agency
      archived the org &mdash; but it&rsquo;s the receipt for a long-running
      claim: I&rsquo;ve been betting on framework-agnostic component
      architecture since 2016. The actual code is below.
    </p>
  </aside>

  <hr class="jm-rule" />

  <h2 class="section-title">what it was</h2>
  <p>
    Skeletor started in 2014 as a project starter &mdash; directory structure,
    Gulp pipeline, Sass utilities, a debug layer, a component loader. The
    initial framing was modest: gather our best practices into a kit so every
    client project didn&rsquo;t reinvent the front end.
  </p>
  <p>
    By 2016 it had grown into a constellation of focused libraries published
    independently:
  </p>

  <dl class="stack-list">
    <dt>core</dt>
    <dd>
      <code>Skeletor.framework</code>, <code>Skeletor.core</code>,
      <code>Skeletor.util.componentLoader</code> &mdash; the runtime,
      registry, and dynamic component loader
    </dd>
    <dt>web components</dt>
    <dd>
      <code>skeletor-plugin-base</code> &mdash; a base class extending
      <code>HTMLElement</code>; <code>skeletor-plugin-accordion</code>,
      <code>Skeletor.flyouts</code>, <code>Skeletor.accordion</code> &mdash;
      working components built on top
    </dd>
    <dt>tokens + design</dt>
    <dd>
      <code>Skeletor.sass.utilities</code>, <code>Skeletor.sass.helpers</code>,
      <code>Skeletor.sass.flexgrid</code> &mdash; a Sass-driven token system
      and grid
    </dd>
    <dt>devx</dt>
    <dd>
      <code>Skeletor.util.debug</code>, <code>Skeletor.docs</code>,
      <code>Skeletor.pluginTemplate</code> &mdash; debugging, documentation
      site, scaffold for new plugins
    </dd>
    <dt>feature detection</dt>
    <dd>
      <code>Skeletor.util.detects.mobile</code>,
      <code>Skeletor.util.detects.flexbox</code> &mdash; the unglamorous
      runtime checks that made the system actually ship cross-browser
    </dd>
  </dl>

  <hr class="jm-rule" />

  <h2 class="section-title">web components in 2016</h2>
  <p>
    The Web Components v1 spec only stabilized in 2018. Lit didn&rsquo;t exist.
    Stencil was a year out. The frameworks-vs-standards debate was still loud.
    Skeletor picked standards. Here&rsquo;s the actual base class from
    <code>skeletor-plugin-base</code> &mdash; December 2016:
  </p>

  <pre><code>{`import $ from 'jquery';
import skeletor from 'skeletor-core';

class SkeletorPlugin extends HTMLElement {

  constructor(element, options){
    super();
    this.NAME = this.constructor.ELEMENT_NAME;
    this.UUID = skeletor.getYoDigits(6, this.NAME);
    this.$element = $(this) || $(document);
    this.options = options;

    if(!this.$element.data('skeletorComponent')){
      this.$element.data('skeletorComponent', this);
    }

    skeletor.registerComponentInstance(this.UUID);
  }

  // web component v1 spec: Fired when custom element is added to DOM.
  connectedCallback() {
    this.init();
  };

  init(){
    console.log('connected:', this);
  }

  static register(){
    let elementName = this.ELEMENT_NAME;
    if(!elementName){
      throw new TypeError(\`You need to define an element name\`);
    }
    skeletor.registerComponent(this, this.ELEMENT_NAME);
  }

  set defaults(value){
    this.options = $.extend(true, {}, value, this.options);
  }
}

export default SkeletorPlugin;`}</code></pre>

  <p>
    <code>extends HTMLElement</code>. <code>connectedCallback</code>.
    Component registry. A self-naming custom element. The same instincts that
    show up in AXS today. The jQuery dependency dates it; the architectural
    choice doesn&rsquo;t.
  </p>

  <hr class="jm-rule" />

  <h2 class="section-title">companion artifacts</h2>
  <p>
    A few sister repos rounded out the story:
  </p>

  <ul class="proof-list">
    <li>
      <strong>accessible-components (2016)</strong> &mdash; a library of WAI-ARIA
      Authoring-Practices-compliant components built on Skeletor. Accessibility
      treated as a baseline, not a feature.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>dd-pattern-library (2017)</strong> &mdash; the agency&rsquo;s pattern
      library, started as a Pattern Lab experiment. The first version of
      &ldquo;design system as an organizational artifact&rdquo; rather than a
      per-project boilerplate.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>on-media-query (2013)</strong> &mdash; an earlier utility for
      triggering JS callbacks on media query state changes. The kind of small
      library that solved a real responsive-design pain point at the time.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <hr class="jm-rule" />

  <h2 class="section-title">what this proved (and what came next)</h2>
  <p>
    Skeletor never had to be a public open-source brand. It was infrastructure
    for one agency&rsquo;s client work, and it did its job well for a few
    years. What matters now is what it shows:
  </p>
  <ul class="proof-list">
    <li>
      <strong>Framework-agnostic component architecture isn&rsquo;t a 2024
      trend for me.</strong> The pattern that powers AXS &mdash; standards-based
      components, framework-light runtime, design tokens via Sass/CSS
      properties &mdash; is the same pattern Skeletor was running in 2016.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>The instinct to build platforms, not features, is durable.</strong>
      Skeletor was always a system, not a project. The reason the AXS work
      worked at Vanguard is the same reason Skeletor worked at the agency:
      separate the substrate from the application code, and let it compound.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Agency speed compounds.</strong> Building on a shared component
      runtime across ~50 client engagements is what taught me what does and
      doesn&rsquo;t survive contact with real delivery pressure. AXS inherited
      those instincts.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <hr class="jm-rule" />

  <h2 class="section-title">stack</h2>
  <dl class="stack-list">
    <dt>Components</dt>
    <dd>Native Web Components (v1 spec), custom elements, shadow DOM-adjacent encapsulation</dd>
    <dt>Build</dt>
    <dd>Gulp 3, JSPM, Bower (yes, Bower), Babel, Sass</dd>
    <dt>Design tokens</dt>
    <dd>Sass utilities + helpers + flexgrid</dd>
    <dt>Distribution</dt>
    <dd>npm + Delphic&rsquo;s internal Bower registry</dd>
    <dt>Documentation</dt>
    <dd>Skeletor.docs (custom site) + the &ldquo;Fednet&rdquo; agency knowledge base</dd>
  </dl>

  <hr class="jm-rule" />

  <p class="project-foot">
    Archived org: <a href="https://github.com/delphic-digital" target="_blank" rel="noopener">github.com/delphic-digital</a>
    &middot; Related work: <a href="/case-studies/02-building-axs">Building AXS</a>
    &middot; <a href="/case-studies/03-framework-agnostic">Framework-Agnostic Architecture</a>
  </p>
</Base>

